<BlogArticle title="Why World Cup 2026 Is Different from Qatar 2022" subtitle="The biggest change is not only tournament size. It is the geography of how supporters must move." category="Transportation Geography" date="June 20, 2026" readingTime="6 min read" tags={['Transportation Geography','World Cup 2026','Air Travel']} image={`${base}research/world-cup-network-hero.png`} imageAlt="Aviation routes connecting cities across North America">
  <p class="lead">In Qatar, aviation brought most international visitors to the tournament. In North America, aviation may also be how many of them move through it.</p>
  <p>That distinction changes the transportation problem. The 2022 World Cup was staged in a country small enough for supporters to sleep in one place and reach different stadiums by metro, shuttle, taxi, or relatively short road trips. The 2026 tournament stretches across Canada, Mexico, and the United States. Its 16 host cities span a continent.</p>
  <p>The result is not simply a larger event. It is a different mobility system.</p>

  <ComparisonMap qatarPoints={qatarPoints} northAmericaPoints={northAmericaPoints} />

  <h2>One metropolitan region, then a continent</h2>
  <p>Qatar used eight stadiums concentrated in and around Doha. The compact venue pattern allowed the tournament to function through a centralized gateway and a dense ground-transportation network. Visitors still faced crowding and peak demand, but attending a second match did not normally require another flight.</p>
  <p>North America reverses that logic. Seattle and Miami are separated by roughly the width of the United States. Vancouver, Mexico City, Boston, Los Angeles, Dallas, and Toronto belong to different regional transportation systems. Even FIFA's regional scheduling cannot eliminate the distances between every team path and knockout destination.</p>
  <div class="comparison">
    <div><span>Transportation factor</span><strong>Qatar 2022</strong><strong>North America 2026</strong></div>
    <div><span>Host geography</span><strong>Compact, centered on Doha</strong><strong>Continental, three countries</strong></div>
    <div><span>Venue pattern</span><strong>8 nearby stadiums</strong><strong>16 separated host cities</strong></div>
    <div><span>Between-match travel</span><strong>Mostly urban ground trips</strong><strong>Long-distance ground trips and flights</strong></div>
    <div><span>Aviation role</span><strong>International gateway</strong><strong>Gateway plus inter-city mobility</strong></div>
    <div><span>Network complexity</span><strong>Centralized</strong><strong>Multiple hubs and national systems</strong></div>
  </div>
  <p class="visual-note">A geographic comparison of tournament mobility. The 2026 schedule has 104 matches across 16 host cities; Qatar 2022 used eight stadiums in one compact host country.</p>

  <h2>Why distance changes fan behavior</h2>
  <p>A conventional tournament trip can be imagined as home, host country, home. A 2026 trip may contain several domestic or international segments inside North America. Supporters who follow a national team may need to move again after each fixture, and knockout destinations depend on results that are unknown when the trip begins.</p>
  <p>This produces a planning problem that is both geographic and temporal. A traveler can know the date of a possible round-of-32 match without knowing the city until the group is settled. Airlines can see the schedule, but not the exact national fan base that will want each route. Airports know their matchdays, but not every onward movement those matches will trigger.</p>
  <p>The uncertainty changes booking behavior. Some supporters will reserve flexible trips early, while others wait for a result and buy the next segment at short notice. A compact tournament can absorb that uncertainty through local movement. A continental tournament translates it into demand for seats between specific city pairs.</p>
  <div class="dark-visual"><div class="flow-stack"><span>Home country<small>International arrival</small></span><i>↓</i><span>First host city<small>Known group-stage match</small></span><i>↓</i><span>Next host city<small>Inter-city air or ground trip</small></span><i>↓</i><span class="active">Knockout destination<small>Conditional on results</small></span><i>↓</i><span>Home<small>Return itinerary</small></span></div></div>

  <h2>Aviation becomes part of the event</h2>
  <p>Large airports give North America enormous capacity and connectivity. That is an advantage: the tournament can draw visitors through many gateways rather than one. Yet the same geography makes the experience more dependent on airline schedules, connecting hubs, airport access, and the cost of repeated travel.</p>
  <p>That dependence will not be equal for every supporter. A fan whose team's matches remain within one region may use rail or road. Another may cross the continent. Price, visa requirements, nonstop service, and the uncertainty of knockout qualification can determine whether someone follows a team or attends only one local match.</p>
  <p>This is why forecasts based only on total attendance can be misleading. The same number of spectators can create very different transportation demand depending on how far they move and how often they change cities.</p>

  <h2>Regional scheduling helps, but does not erase distance</h2>
  <p>FIFA grouped many fixtures into western, central, and eastern zones to limit unnecessary travel. That is a meaningful design choice. A team whose group matches remain in one zone creates less movement than one repeatedly crossing the continent.</p>
  <p>Yet regionalization has limits. The knockout bracket reconnects the tournament at a continental scale, and supporters do not all begin inside the host region. Toronto and New York are comparatively close; Seattle and Los Angeles belong to the same broad western zone but are still far enough apart that flying can be the practical choice. Dallas and Houston are connected by road, while Boston to Miami is a different transportation decision entirely.</p>
  <p>The host-city label can also hide metropolitan geography. The Dallas stadium is in Arlington, the Boston venue is in Foxborough, and the New York/New Jersey stadium is in East Rutherford. Air travel reaches the metropolitan region, not the stadium gate. Each aviation trip still requires a final surface journey whose time and reliability vary by city.</p>

  <h2>Who can follow a team?</h2>
  <p>Geography is also an access question. Repeated flights add airfare, baggage costs, airport transfers, and the risk of a missed segment. International visitors may have already paid for a long-haul ticket before deciding whether they can afford to follow a team between cities.</p>
  <p>That can change who appears in the stands. Wealthier supporters may build multi-city itineraries, while others choose one match or one region. Local spectators can fill seats without generating the hotel nights or inter-city aviation demand expected from international fans. A sold-out stadium therefore does not automatically imply the same mobility pattern in every host city.</p>
  <p>Transportation geography shapes participation long before kickoff. The relevant question is not only how many tickets are sold, but how many city changes a supporter can realistically make.</p>

  <h2>What geography reveals</h2>
  <p>The compact 2022 tournament concentrated pressure around one metropolitan system. The 2026 tournament distributes pressure across gateways, airline hubs, highways, border crossings, and local transit networks. Distribution can prevent one city from carrying the entire event, but it also creates many more connections that have to work.</p>
  <p>The biggest difference between the two tournaments is not only football expansion. It is geography. Qatar treated aviation primarily as the front door. North America makes aviation part of the hallway between rooms.</p>

